{
  "doc_id": "34696",
  "text": "Currently, HSCs are expanded in the presence of a combination of cytokines [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, under in vivo conditions, HSCs are reliant upon the cytokines and also on the varied components from their niche, such as mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs), endothelial cells, osteoblasts, etc., and extra cellular matrix for their maintenance and differentiation [CITATION_4] . This emphasizes the need for an optimized culture system which closely resembles the in vivo niche and supports the growth of HSCs in vitro. Various cell types from the niche are used for the expansion of HSCs, but MSCs in particular are found to be efficient in sustaining the ex vivo expansion of HSCs [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
